ality: Possession as Indigenous Historiography -- t18 Possession, Communication and Power in Himachal Pradesh (North India) -- t19 A Day-to-Day Family Chronicle with “Personages” in Madagascar -- t20 Anthropological Spirits and Colonial Consciousness in Arabic- Speaking Sudan -- t21 From Illness to Trance -- t22 On Spirit Possession and Some Parallels with Reincarnation -- tContributors -- tName Index -- tSubject Index -- tGeographical Index0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aPossession, a seemingly irrational phenomenon, has posed challenges to generations of scholars rooted in Western notions of body-soul dualism, self and personhood, and a whole set of presuppositions inherited from Christian models of possession that was “good” or “bad.” The authors of the essays in this book present a new and more promising approach. They conceive spirit possession as a form of communication, of expressivity, of culturally defined behavior that should be understood in the context of local, vernacular theories and empiric reflections. With the aim of reformulating the comparative anthropology of spirit possession, the editors have opened corridors between previously separate areas of research. Together, anthropologists and historians working on several historical periods and in different European, African, South American, and Asian cultural areas attempt to redefine the very concept of possession, freeing it from the Western notion of the self and more clearly delineating it from related matters such as witchcraft, devotion, or mysticism. The book also provides an overview of new research directions, including novel methods of participant observation and approaches to spirit possession as indigenous historiography  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Mrz 2023) 0aSpirit possession. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh  aExorcism, body & soul, rites, demons, trance, medium, participant observation.1 aBehrend, Heike, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBerti, Daniela, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBoddy, Janice, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBárth, Dániel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCaciola, Nancy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCastel, Pierre-Henri, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChave-Mahir, Florence, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCsordas, Thomas J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFerber, Sarah, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFiéloux, Michèle, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFröhlich, Ida, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKeller, Mary L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKlaniczay, Gábor, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLambek, Michael, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLombard, Jacques, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPócs, Éva, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPócs, Éva, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aRivière, Janine, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSchmidt, Bettina E., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aTarabout, Gilles, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aTimotin, Emanuela, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWorobec, Christine D., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.l